sentence-detokenized: The EU rejects Germany's call to boycott British lamb.
Peter Blackburn
BRYSSEL 1996-08-22

The European Commission said on Thursday it disagreed with German advice that consumers should avoid British lamb until scientists have established whether mad cow disease can be transmitted to sheep.

Germany's representative on the European Union's veterinary committee, Werner Zwingmann, said on Wednesday that consumers should buy sheepmeat from countries other than Britain until scientific advice is clearer.
"We do not support any such recommendation because we see no justification for it," Commission spokesman Nikolaus van der Pas told a news conference.
He said that more scientific studies are needed and if it is found that action is needed, the European Union should take it.

He said last month's proposal by EU Agriculture Commissioner Franz Fischler to ban sheep brain, spleen and spinal cord from the human and animal food chain was a very precise and precautionary measure to protect human health.
Fischler proposed EU-wide measures following reports from Britain and France that sheep could contract bovine spongiform encephalopathy (BSE), or mad cow disease, under laboratory conditions.

However, Fischler agreed to revise his proposal after the EU Standing Veterinary Committee and national animal health authorities questioned whether such action was justified given the low risk to human health.
Spanish Agriculture Minister Loyola de Palacio had earlier accused Fischler of causing unwarranted alarm at a meeting of EU agriculture ministers with a "dangerous generalisation".
Only France and the United Kingdom supported Fischler's proposal.
The EU's Scientific and Multidisciplinary Veterinary Committee is due to review the issue early next month and make recommendations to the highest veterinary authorities.
Sheep have long been known to contract scrapie, a brain-destroying disease similar to BSE, which is believed to have been passed on to cattle through feed containing animal waste.

British farmers denied on Thursday that their sheep pose a risk to human health, but expressed concern that the German government's advice to consumers to avoid British lamb could affect consumers across Europe.
"We have to be very careful about how other countries take their lead from Germany," John Lloyd Jones, President of the National Farmers' Union (NFU) in Wales, told BBC radio.

Bonn has led efforts to protect public health after consumer confidence plummeted in March following a British report that people could contract a disease like mad cow disease by eating contaminated beef.
Germany imported 47 600 sheep from the UK last year, almost half of the total.
It imported 4 275 tonnes of British sheepmeat, around 10% of total imports.
A rare sketch of a Hendrix song sells for nearly $17 000.
A rare handwritten draft of a song by US guitar legend Jimi Hendrix sold for nearly $17 000 on Thursday at an auction of the late musician's favourite artefacts.
A Florida restaurant paid £10 925 ($16 935) for a draft of "Ain't no telling", which Hendrix wrote on London hotel stationery in late 1966.
At the end of a concert in Nottingham, England, in January 1967, he threw a sheet of paper into the audience, where a fan retrieved it.
The buyers also snapped up 16 other items put up for auction by Hendrix's ex-girlfriend Kathy Etchingham, who lived with Hendrix from 1966 to 1969.
They included a black lacquer and pearl-encrusted box used by Hendrix to store his drugs, which was bought by an anonymous Australian buyer for £5,060 ($7,845).
The guitarist died of a drug overdose in 1970 at the age of 27.
China says Taiwan is spoiling the negotiating atmosphere.
BEIJING 1996-08-22
China accused Taipei on Thursday of spoiling the atmosphere for resuming talks across the Taiwan Strait with a visit to Ukraine by Taiwan Vice President Lien Chan this week that angered Beijing.

Foreign Ministry spokesman Shen Guofang told Reuters just hours after Chinese state media said it was time to start political talks with Taiwan: "Taiwanese authorities have disrupted the atmosphere necessary for the start of negotiations".
State media quoted Tang Shube, the top negotiator between China and Taipei, as telling a group visiting Taiwan on Wednesday that it was time for the rivals to hold political talks.
"Now is the time for both sides to start political negotiations...
which is an end to hostility," Thursday's foreign edition of People's Daily quoted Tang as saying.

Foreign Ministry's Shen told Reuters in an interview that he had read reports of Tang's comments, but he did not give details of why the negotiator had felt the time was right for talks with Taiwan, which Beijing considers a renegade province.
China, which has long opposed any attempt by Taipei to gain more international recognition, was outraged by Taiwan's Vice President Lien's visit to Ukraine this week.
China says the time is right for Taiwan talks.
BEIJING 1996-08-22
China has said it is time for political talks with Taiwan and that the rival island should take practical steps to achieve this.

Negotiations should be held to determine the timing and format of the talks, the official Xinhua news agency quoted Tang Shubei, vice chairman of the Taiwan Straits Cross-Strait Relations Association, as saying late Wednesday.
German car registrations in July rose by 14.2% year-on-year.
FRANKFURT 1996-08-22
First registrations of motor vehicles in Germany rose 14.2 percent year-on-year in July this year, the Federal Motor Vehicle Office said on Thursday.
According to the Agency, 356 725 new cars were registered in July 1996, of which 304 850 were passenger cars and 15 613 were lorries.
The increase was 13.6% for passenger cars and 2.2% for lorries compared to July 1995.
Motorcycle registrations increased by 32.7% over the same period.
According to the federal agency, the increase was partly due to more Germans buying German cars abroad, while manufacturers reported weak domestic demand.
Almost all German car manufacturers saw an increase in registrations over the period.
Volkswagen AG received 77 719 registrations, which is just over a quarter of all registrations.
Opel AG, together with General Motors, came in second with 49 269 registrations, 16.4% of the total.
Ford was third with 35 563 registrations, or 11.7%.
Only Seat and Porsche registrations were down in July 1996 compared to July last year.
Seat recorded 3,420 registrations, compared to 5,522 a year earlier in July.
Porsche registrations fell to 554 from 643.

Israel downplays fears of war with Syria.
Colleen Siegel
JERUSALEM 1996-08-22
The outgoing Israeli-Syrian peace negotiator said on Thursday that the current tensions between the two countries appeared to be a storm in a teacup.
Itamar Rabinovich, who as Israeli ambassador in Washington held fruitless talks with Syria, told Israeli radio that it seemed that Damascus preferred to talk rather than fight.
"It seems to me that {(1)[MISC] Syria's priority} is still to negotiate.
The Syrians are confused, they are certainly tense, but the general assessment here in Washington is that this is more like a storm in a teacup," he said.
Rabinovich's term as ambassador is coming to an end.
He will be replaced by Eliahu Ben-Elissar, former Israeli envoy to Egypt and a right-wing Likud politician.
On Wednesday, Israel sent a message to Syria via Washington, expressing its commitment to peace and its willingness to start negotiations without preconditions.
However, it criticised Damascus for creating a dangerous atmosphere.
Syria on Wednesday accused Israel of a hysterical campaign against it after Israeli television reported that Damascus had recently test-fired a missile.
It said its arms purchases were for defence purposes.

"The message we sent to (Syrian President Hafez al-) Assad is that Israel is ready to start peace talks at any time without preconditions," Israeli Foreign Minister David Levy said in an interview with Israel Radio.
Tensions have increased since Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu took office in June and vowed to preserve the Golan Heights, which Israel captured from Syria in the 1967 Middle East war.
Peace talks between Israel and Syria have been deadlocked over the Golan since 1991, despite the previous government's willingness to make concessions on the Golan.
Peace talks between the parties were last held in February.
"The sounds coming from Damascus are bad, not good.
Media...
are full of expressions and declarations that must be worrying...
this artificial climate is very dangerous because those who spread it can become its prisoners," Levy said.
"We expect Syria, if it is peace-minded, to respond to Israel's message to start peace talks, because that is our goal," he said. "
We don't want war, God forbid.
Nobody benefits from wars. "
Israel's Channel Two television said Damascus had sent Israel a "reassuring message".
It did not indicate the source of the report.
Spokesmen for Netanyahu and Levy said they could not confirm.
Television also reported that Netanyahu had sent messages to pacify Syria via Cairo, the United States and Moscow.
A Polish diplomat denies the presence of nurses in Libya.
TUNISIA 1996-08-22

A Polish diplomat on Thursday denied a report published in a Polish daily newspaper this week that Libya had refused to grant exit visas to 100 Polish nurses seeking to return home after working in the North African country.
"This is not true.

So far we have not received any information about a single nurse who has been stranded or detained in Libya against his will, and we have not received any complaints," Tadeusz Awdankiewicz, the Polish embassy's Chargé d'Affaires in Tripoli, told Reuters by telephone.

The Polish Labour Ministry announced this week that it would send a team to Libya to investigate, but according to Awdankiewicz, the investigation was prompted by complaints from some nurses about working conditions, including non-payment of wages.
According to him, there are an estimated 800 Polish nurses working in Libya.
Two Iranian opposition leaders meet in Baghdad.
Hassan Hafidh
BAGHDAD 1996-08-22
An Iranian exile group based in Iraq vowed on Thursday to expand its support for Iran's Kurdish rebels after Iranian forces attacked them deep inside Iraq last month.

Mujahideen Khalq said in a statement that its leader Massoud Rajavi met on Wednesday in Baghdad with Hassan Rastegar, Secretary General of the Kurdistan Democratic Party of Iran (KDPI), and expressed his support for the Kurdish rebels in Iran.
"Rajavi stressed that the Iranian resistance movement continues to stand side by side with its Kurdish compatriots and the Iranian Kurdistan resistance movement," it said.
A spokesman for the group said the meeting "marks a new level of cooperation between the Mujahideen Khalq and Iran's Kurdish opponents".
Iran heavily bombed targets in northern Iraq in July in pursuit of KDPI guerrillas operating in Iraqi Kurdish areas outside Baghdad government control.
The Iraqi Kurdish areas bordering Iran are held by the guerrilla group of the Patriotic Union of Iraqi Kurds (PUK).
The PUK and the Kurdistan Democratic Party of Iraq (KDP), Iraq's two main Kurdish factions, have controlled northern Iraq since Iraqi forces were ousted from Kuwait in the 1991 Gulf War.
Clashes between the two sides erupted over the weekend in the most serious fighting since the US ceasefire last year.
According to Mujahideen Khalq, Iranian forces have also bombed KDP positions in the Qasr district of Suleimaniya province near the Iranian border over the past two days.
According to the report, around 100 Iraqi Kurds were killed or wounded in the attack.
Both Iran and Turkey are carrying out air and ground attacks on targets in northern Iraq in pursuit of their own Kurdish rebels.
In southern Turkey, the US-led air force protects Iraqi Kurds from possible attacks by Baghdad forces.
The Saudi rial is stable in quiet summer trade.
The Saudi rial's spot rate against the dollar and the rial's interbank deposit rates were broadly stable this week in quiet summer trading, dealers in the Kingdom said.
"There was no change in the Saudi rial exchange rate.
The market was very quiet because of the summer holidays," said one dealer.
Spot riyal was put at 3,7504 / 06 dollars.
One-month interbank deposits were 5-1/2, 3/8 percent, three-month deposits 5-5/8, 1/2 percent and six-month deposits 5-3/4, 5/8 percent.
One-year funds were up six, 5-7/8 percent.
Israel approves Arafat's flight to the West Bank.
JERUSALEM 1996-08-22
Israel on Thursday gave Palestinian President Yasser Arafat permission to fly over its territory to the West Bank, ending a brief crisis between Israel and the PLO, an adviser to Arafat said.
"The problem is over.
The president's plane has been cleared to pass through Israeli airspace, but he is not expected to travel to the West Bank until Monday," Nabil Abu Rdainah told Reuters.

Mr Arafat was due to meet former Israeli Prime Minister Shimon Peres in Ramallah in the West Bank on Thursday, but the venue was changed to Gaza after Israel refused to allow the Palestinian leader to fly helicopters.
Palestinian officials accused right-wing Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu of trying to block the Ramallah meeting by keeping Arafat in the country.
Arafat then cancelled a meeting between Israeli and PLO officials on civilian matters at the Allenby Bridge at the Jordan-West Bank crossing.
Abu Rdainah said Arafat had decided not to fly to the West Bank on Thursday after Israel lifted the ban because he had a busy schedule in Gaza and would not be free until Monday.
Arafat meets Peres in Gaza after the flight ban.
JERUSALEM 1996-08-22

Yasser Arafat will meet Shimon Peres in Gaza on Thursday, after Palestinians reported that Israel's right-wing government had prevented the Palestinian leader from flying to the West Bank for talks with the former prime minister.
